@txt:«We have three main goals: close down the Student Parliament, put an end to unprofitable studies, and end the SiO monopoly,» said Johan Hertzberg, a member of the new Fremskritts party at UiO.

@spm:Why?

@txt:«The Student Parliament is defective. It’s only for those who want to pad their CV, get free pizza, and grant money to themselves.»
He claims the student politicians talk about things the students don’t really care about and draws particular attention to what he thinks is an unnecessary waste of money:
«The leaders earn wages of up to 25,000 NOK per month.»

@mt:«We deserve food»

@txt:The leader for the Student Parliament, Jens Lægreid, welcomes the new party and believes they have an interest to work constructively.

[[ quote-1 ]]

@spm:What do you think about their wish to close down the Student Parliament?

@txt:«It’s unfortunate that they don’t see the value in the Student Parliament, but we hope they will discover the value after they have worked with us»
Lægreid does not agree with the description that the Student Parliament only is a place to pad one’s CV and get free pizza.
«My experience is that people join the Student Parliament on the basis of a genuine commitment to the students, and they sure deserve some food after the long hours they invest in this community.»

@mt:Subsidized coffee

@txt:Hertzberg thinks it would be better to increase the power for the student representors around the different boards around UiO where the facilities and the university can address about concerns from students.
«The students have to use their voices, they don’t do that today. The Student Parliament has little knowledge about their opinions and what resolutions they adopt,» Hertzberg said, referring to the case of the academic boycott of Israel, when the Student Parliament [went back on their own decision.](1)

@spm:What would the money allocated for the Student Parliament go to instead?

@txt:«They could go to a lot of different things, for example student housing, scholarships or subsidized coffee,» says Hertzberg.

@mt:Wants to pay for his own pizza

@txt:It’s well known that the Student Parliament struggles with very low engagement in elections. Only 17.6 percent of the students at UiO participated in the last election.
«I think we can increase the general participation around the elections by mobilize the students who show low interest today, which is more than 80 percent of the students,» said Hertzberg and add that the new party will work for their other goals if they don’t succeed in shutting down the Student Parliament.

@spm:Could there be a risk that Fremskritts party will just become a part of the game?

@txt:«I will never receive a single krone from the Student Parliament in allowance. And I will pay for my own pizza.»

@txt:The Easter break is over and we are just beginning to see the start of Spring. Perhaps international students have visited friends and family, relaxed over the extended break and just generally over-indulged and gorged themselves on Easter treats. Compared to that, returning to Oslo to begin studies again may seem a little dreary, so here are Inter Universitas’ Top Five Tips to beat the post-Easter blues. Embrace the paradoxical snow and sun that is peculiar to Oslo in April.

@tingo:1. Toboggan run (Korketrekkeren). Ridiculously fun at any point in the winter season, but especially over the Easter break with the added benefit of the sun shining. Take a group of friends up to Frognerseteren T-bane, and sled down the exciting (and slightly terrifying) course. When you get to the bottom take the T-bane back to the top of the slope from Midtstuen. A standard Zone 1 Ruter Card includes the price of this journey and the run is free to ride, but the toboggan rental costs between 100-150 NOK, or you can bring your own. The charity organisers Akeforeningen update their website with sledding conditions and availability, so make sure to check that out first.

@tingo:2. The Norwegian Trekking Association (DNT). With a membership and a bit of know-how, you can use one of the 500 cabins that the association has to offer. Around 450 of them are non-staffed, so make sure you do your research beforehand. The membership gives you access to a skeleton key which can be used to unlock the numerous cabins. Grab a group of friends and go and explore the Norwegian wilderness!

@tingo:3. Cross country skiing in the sunshine. Although it is the end of the season now, the particularly chilly winter has left plenty of tracks still available. The Association for the promotion of skiing (Skiforeningen) has loads of suggestions on where to go. Students are able to rent skis from SIO at a very reasonable price, and the Oslo Ski Centre also offers complete equipment rental.

@tingo:4. Loppedmarker. This is possibly the most useful thing for international students here in Oslo. Many schools open their doors in April to host flea markets and jumble sales. The products range is anything from kitchenware to water-skiing equipment and as it is second hand everything is ridiculously cheap. Look through the Loppemarkeder website to find the one nearest to you.

@tingo:5. City Bikes. The start of April means those bright blue bikes will once again be dotted all around the city. For the low price of 399 NOK you can register for the whole season (April-November) and pick up a bike from any of the 200 stations. Bygdøy is a particularly beautiful area to explore by bicycle, or just use them to get to school and enjoy the sunshine.
